<!-- CHERNOBYL -->
<article class="event" id="event-chernobyl">
  <header>
    <h3><time datetime="1986-04-26">26 April 1986</time> — Chernobyl</h3>
  </header>
  <p>
    The explosion at Reactor No. 4 of the Chernobyl Nuclear Power Plant occurred
    during a safety test — specifically a test to see whether the reactor could
    be safely powered down in a controlled way. The test was run by operators
    who did not fully understand the reactor's physics, particularly a design
    characteristic called positive void coefficient that made the reactor
    unstable at low power. Soviet institutional culture made stopping or
    questioning the test politically unacceptable. The signals — procedure,
    schedule, authority — overrode the mechanism. The long-term death toll from
    radiation exposure remains contested, ranging from tens to potentially
    hundreds of thousands depending on methodology.
  </p>
  <nav aria-label="Chernobyl sources">
    <ul>
      <li>
        <a href="https://www.iaea.org/topics/chernobyl" rel="external"
          >IAEA — International Atomic Energy Agency official summary</a
        >
      </li>
      <li>
        <a
          href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chernobyl_disaster"
          rel="external">Wikipedia: Chernobyl disaster</a
        >
      </li>
      <li>
        <a
          href="https://www.who.int/news/item/05-09-2005-chernobyl-the-true-scale-of-the-accident"
          rel="external"
          >WHO — "Chernobyl: the true scale of the accident" (2005)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
  </nav>
  <aside class="source-note" role="note">
    <span class="provenance-label">Source note</span>
    <span class="provenance-text">
      Death toll estimates vary enormously and are politically charged. The
      IAEA/WHO joint report (2005) estimated approximately 4,000 eventual deaths
      among those most exposed. Greenpeace and some independent researchers
      estimate far higher numbers. The methodology dispute is itself worth
      reading about.
    </span>
  </aside>
</article>

<!-- BHOPAL -->
<article class="event" id="event-bhopal">
  <header>
    <h3><time datetime="1984-12-03">3 December 1984</time> — Bhopal</h3>
  </header>
  <p>
    The Union Carbide pesticide plant in Bhopal, India, released approximately
    40 tonnes of methyl isocyanate gas into a densely populated area. Safety
    systems at the plant had been documented as failing for months. Cost-cutting
    had disabled or degraded multiple backup systems. Local management knew. The
    signal — profitable operation, schedule, cost reduction — drowned out the
    mechanism. Immediate death toll estimates range from 3,800 to over 15,000.
    Long-term health impacts continue to affect the surrounding population.
  </p>
  <nav aria-label="Bhopal sources">
    <ul>
